{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170963/1937102101/0580.xml":{"full_text":"6\nROOSEVELT DEFICIT\nPREDICTION REVIVES\nTALK OF TAX RAISE\n\nCongressional Approval df\nIncrease in Levies Debated\n\u2014Tax Probers Deep in\nRevenue Proposals\nWashington. Oct. IS\u2014(AP)\u2014Presi\ndent Roosevelt's forecast of a federal\ndeficit larger than expected for this\nfiscal year revived dehate tonight as\nto whether Congress should enact ad\nditional taxes to meet expenses.\nSome of the administration's chief\nfiscal officers have urged a balanced\nbudget, next .vear even it it requires\nnew and heavier levies. Congressional\nleaders generally contend a balance\ncan be achieved without new taxes.\nTreasury and congressional experts\nare :iy L L: A -vision of\nthe tax structure at the regular ses\nsion of Congress beginning in Jan-\nuary.\nKnee-Deep In Dispute\nThe tax study Is knee-deep in dis\npute over revision of the undistributed\nprofits, tax. socalled \"nuisance\" taxes,\nproposed codification of the revenue\nlaws, the capital gains and com\nmunity property taxes and the stormy\nsubject of reductions allowed mining\nand oil companies tor depletion.\nIn studying a long-range program,\nthe joint congressional tax commit\ntee has emphasized that it seeks a\nprogram \"designated to permit rate\nchanges to meet varying economic\nconditions without, changing the form\nof taxation.\"\nSenator LaFo'.lette (Prog., Wis.)\nrecently came forward with a renewed\ndemand for a broader income tax base\nand higher surtaxes on middle bracket\nIncomes. He said $110,000,000 of new\nrevenue could be brought in by reduc\ning the personal exemption of mar\nried taxpayers from $2500 to S2OOO\nand the exemption for single persons\nfrom SIOOO to SBOO.\nThe committee has been reviewing\nthe income surtax rates on individ\nuals. They now range from 4 per cent\nof net incomes between 84000 and\nS6OOO and 75 per cent of net incomes\nover $5,000,000. La Follette said his\nproposal to increase would produce\n$247,800,000 of new\" revenue.\nKing\u2019s Forecast Recalled\nSenator King (D., Utah), ranking\nmajority member of the Senate\nfinance committee, has forecast Con\ngress will find it necessary to lower\nIncome tax exemptions so as to reach\nmore taxpayers. He talked also of re\npealing the capital gains tax and\nmaking material changes in the un\ndistributed profits tax.\nRepresentative Celler (D.. N. Y.)\ncontends repeal of the capital gains\ntax would be a powerful business\nstimulant, possibly yielding the treas\nury an additional $250,000,000 in col\nlections from other levies.\nThe committee has heard discussion\nof a proposed constitutional amend\nment providing a two-way taxing\npower for federal and state levies\non now exempt securities. In 1935. it\nis estimated, there were outstand\ning more than $50,000,000,000 of ex\nempt and partially exempt federal\nand state securities on which holders\npaid no tax tor the interest they\nreceived.\nAlso. the proposed amendment\nwould lift income tax exemptions en\njoyed by more than 6,000,000 federal\nstate and local employes.\nUNLIMITED FUNDS\u2019\nTO BACK CAMPAIGN\nAGAINSTPARALYSIS\n30 of America's Richest\nMen Volunteer as Trustees\nof Roosevelt\u2019s Newly-Or\nganized Foundation\nNew York. Oct. 14 President\nRoosevelt will shortly announce the\nnames of some 30 of America\u2019s richest\nmen who have volunteered to serve\nas trustees of his newly-organized\nfoundation to coordinate the battle of\nmedical scientists throughout the na\nt(pn against infantile paralysis.\nThis was revealed here tonight fol\nlowing the disclosure at Chicago by\nDr John Paul de Kruif of Holland,\nMich., noted bacteriologist and secre\ntary of the President's infantile par\nalysis research commission, that the\nplan -will be underwritten by almost\n\"unlimited funds.\"\nWhile the names of the trustees\nare being kept a closely guarded se\ncret by the commission headquarters\nhere, it was reliably learned that the\ngroup of capitalists who are prepared\nto open their pocke,tbooks wide in the\nbehalf ot a scientific campaign include\nsome prominent men whose political\nfaith is the opposite of the Pres\nident's.\nUnified Action Sought\nPresident Roosevelt, long interested\nin combatting the disease with which\nhe was himself once stricken, is mar\nshaling all the forces of scientific re\nsearch and medical practice in an ef\nfort to unify their activities in the\nspeediest possible fight on infantile\nparalysis.\nThe new foundation, which has not\nyet been given Its official name, will\nhave the fullest cooperation from such\norganizations as the Rockefeller foun\ndation, which is already financing in\ndependent channels of research in\nsearch of a positive cure for the\ndisease.\nThe United States public health\nservice in Washington will also coop\nerate as will the Warm Springs foun\ndation of Georgia, in which the Pres\nident has been interested.\nSome successful experiments, al\nready under way at Columbia univer\nsity here under joint auspices of the\nRockefeller foundation and the Pres\nident\u2019s birthday ball commission tor\ninfantile paralysis, have Indicated\npromising curative qualities in vita\nmin C.\nVitamin C Is Tested\nProf Claus W. Jungeblut of Colum\nbia\u2019s bacteriology department, has\nbeen experimenting with vitamin C\non several hundred monkeys in his\nlaboratory He has found that an In\njection of \"natural vitamin C\" ex\ntracted from fruits and vegetables\nwas a powerful factor in combatting\ninfantile paralysis.\nPlans are to wage a practical, im\nmediate fight on Infantile in every\ncommunity where the disease broke\nout. this summer, at the same time\nthe scientific brains of the nation are\nmustered in a unified laboratory \"war\"\non the scourge.\nPreventive treatments will be given\nchildren at free clinics and first-class\nmedical aid offered those who have\ncontracted the disease. Special insti\ntutions wiy be developed tor rehabill\ntat ion of those left crippled by the\ndisease\n(Copyright, 1817, by INS)\nMore Hollywood Pay\nBrings Added Luxury\nOf Couch for Office\nHollywood, Oct. 14\u2014Entry into\nthe high salary brackets of\nscenario writing brings the added\nprestige of having an office couch.\nSherman L. Lowe, scenarist,\nrevealed today.\nTestifying at h labor board\nhearing. Lowe said that when\nhe was paid SBS a week he\npunched a studio time clock and\nhad no couch in his office. Non\nin the $l5O a week bracket. Lowe\nsaid, he has a couch and can\nenjoy the luxury of an occasional\nnap on office time.\nIn the jurisdictional dispute be\ntween the Studios and Screen\nPlaywrights, Inc., against the\nScreen Writers\u2019 guild, the. former\nclaim that persons who are pro\nvided with couches do not con\nstitute a labor group within the\nmeaning of the law.\nMEDICAL JOURNAL\nWARNS PUBLIC OF\nDRUG AS EIGHT DIE\n\nSulfanilamide Preparation\nBlamed in Tulsa (Old.)\nDeaths\u2014-Drug Store Ship\nments Recalled\nChicago, Oct. 18\u2014(AP) \u2014The Ameri-\nI can Medical association warned pub\ni licly today of a drug preparation\nwhich the Association said apparently\ncaused eight deaths in Tulsa. Oki.,\nand which had been widely distributed\ni elsewhere.\nDr Morris Fishbein, editor of the\nJournal of the American Medical as\nsociation, released \"for the protection\nof the public\" an editorial to be pub\ni lished in the Journal, attributing the\ndeaths to an elixir of sulfanilamide.\nDr Fishbein said the preparation in\nquestion was only recently placed on\nthe market by one firm and that 375\nshipments had been made to drug\nstores throughout the country. These\nshipments, he said, were being re\ncalled.\nDr Fishbein explained sulfanilamide\nis a \"very valuable\u201d new drug used\nprincipally in treatment of streptococ- I\ncus infections, meningitis and gonor\nrhea. but that it can have dangerous i\neffects when used in improper quanti- I\nties and without a doctor's advice.\nMany medical supply houses distribute\nthe drug, usually in tablet form, he i\nsaid. It is sold in drugstores. Dr i\nFishbein explained, either with or j\nwithout a physician's prescription.\nApparently Poisoned by Elixir\n\"Eight out of 10 persons who have\nbeen given a proprietary eixir of,\nsulfanilamide died recently in Tulsa.\nOki.. from anuria which apparently\nresulted directly from poisoning by\nthis elixir.\" the editorial said. \"One i\nof the remaining two patients has I\nrecovered and the prognosis for the I\nother one is not considered favor- I\nable.\n\u201cFrom tests by the laboratory of\nthe American Medical association this\nelixir appears to be a solution of ap-\nproximately 40 grains of sulfanilamide\nto a fluid ounce of menstrum contain\ning about 7 2 per cent diethylene\nglycol.\n\"The solvent, diethylene glycol, is i\nI itself not an indifferent substance, its\nuse is not permitted in food products\nbecause of the absence of any\nI scientific evidence establishing its\nharmlessness beyond doubt. It\nwould appear to be clear that the I\ndiethylene glycol rather than the sul-\nfanilamide was responsible (for the I\nTulsa deaths) since one of the i\npatients had received tablets over a 1\nperiod of two weeks without any oad\neffects and then developed the typical\ntrain of symptoms after taking the\nelixir.\nURGES MUTUAL\nUNDERSTANDING\nFOR HEMISPHERE\nSecretary Hull Appeals to\nAmericas for \u2018System Proof;\nAgainst Shocks\u2019 in Broad\ncast\nWashington, Oct. 15\u2014(AP)\u2014Secre- j\ntary Hull commended to the 21\nAmerican republics tonight an \"Inter-\nnational system so firmly grounded\nin understandings that it will be proof I\nagainst any shocks to which it may\nbe subjected.\"\nInaugurating a series of regular\nbroadcasts to Latin America under\nauspices of the Pan-American union,\nthe secretary of state characterized\nradio communication among the va\nrious countries as an Important factor I\nin the achievement of such an ob\njective.\n\u201cAs yet,\u201d he asserted, \"we have I\nhardly begun to fathom the possl- I\nbilities of radio communication as a\nfactor In the development of inter- I\nnational good will and understanding.\n\u201cThrough the new series of pro- I\ngrams which the Pan-American union\nis Inaugurating today, we are taking\nan important step In the fulfillment\nof the resolutions of the Montevideo 1\nand Buenos Aires conferences.\"\n\u201cEnlightened Ptihlle Opinion\u201d\n(He referred to the Pan-American\nI conference at Montevideo in 1933 and\nIto the inter-American peace confer- I\nence at Buenos Aires last Uecember. j\nboth of which he attended.)\nHull spoke as chairman of the Pan- i\nAmerican union\u2019s governing board. i\n\"This new instrumentality,\" he said, j\n\u201cpossesses a special significance for j\nthe American republics. In our demo-\ncraeles, in which we seek to have\npublic opinion guide both domestic i\nand foreign policy, it is of vital im\nportance that there should be an en\nlightened public opinion that is kept\nin touch with the trend of national\nthought and with the outstanding de\nvelopments ot the national life of\nother peoples.\n\u201cOnly in this way can we hope to\nI build up an international system so\nfirmly grounded in mutual understand-\nI ing that it will be proof against any\nshocks to which it may be subjected.\"\nWORK OF DAN CUPID\nSPEEDED UP BY PWA\nOmhaha. Neb., Oct. 17\u2014(AP)\u2014When\nofficials told Donald Butler, 22. of Oma\nha, he couldn't get a PWA Job\nbecause he didn't have a wife, he\nwent right out and got married\nsomething he had wanted to do for\nsome time.\nHis bride was 14-year-old Audrey\nMae Eden. They had to go to lowa\nto be wed as Nebraska law sets the\ni feminine marriage age limit at 13,\nI even with parents\u2019 consent.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN; SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, OCTOBER 21, 193 T\nTELEGRAM SEIZURE\nBY SEC IS UPHELD\nBY SUPREME COURT\nFlorida Companies Fail to\nPrevent Subpoenas\nBlack's Participation May\nBring Challenge\nWashington. Oct. 18\u2014(AP) \u2014A plea\nby three Florida companies that the\nsecurities commission be prevented\nfrom subpoenaing their telegraphic\ncorrespondence proved fruitless in the\nj supreme court today.\nThe tribunal refused to review the\nlease, thus permitting a lower court\ndecision against the companies to\nI stand.\nThe refusal aroused speculation as\nto whether the companies would chal\ni lenge the ruling because Justice Hugo\n1\nBlack formerly was chairman of a\nSenate lobby committee which ex\namined telegrams received and sent\nIby persons under its scrutiny. The\ntelegrams were obtained by the lobby\ninvestigators with the aid of the com\nmunications commission.\nOther Rulings\nIt was assumed generally that Black\ntook part in today's ruling because\nthe court made no announcement to\nthe contrary. Customarily, when a jus\ntice does not participate in a decision\nit is so announced.\nThe Florida case came before the\nhigh tribunal from the fifth circuit\ncourt of appeals, which upheld the\nsubpoenas of the telegrams and sus\ntained the securities act of 1933. The\nsubpoenas were issued under that law.\nIn other rulings today the supreme\ncourt:\nDismissed an appeal by Lawrence\nHanfgarn. of Floral Park, L. 1., who\nchallenged the constitutionality of a\n1935 New York law barring civil ac\ntions for alienation of affections, se\nduction and breach of promise. The\nsupreme court held that Hanfgarn's\ncase presented no \"substantial federal\nquestion.\u201d I\nRefused to review a decision of the\nfourth circuit court of appeals against\nthe Jeffersy-DeWltt insulator com- I\npany. of Kenova, W. Va. The company\nhad appealed an order of the labor\nrelations board declaring it guilty of\nunfair labor practices.\nEXPERTS MINIMIZE\nTRADE EFFECT OF\nBIG ARMS PROJECT\nSay Rearmament Would Ac\ncount for Only $300,000,-\n000, Including New Ships,\nExperiment Costs\nNew York. Oct. 13\u2014(AP)\u2014While\nthe special session of Congress called\nyesterday for November 15 brings up\nthe possibility of an early authoriza\ntion for a heavy armaments-building\nprogram, experts are inclined to min\nimize its bearing on the 1938 business\noutlook.\nThere have been rumors recently\na $2,000,000,000 expenditure for re\narmament might be sought in Con\ngress, a program comparable to the\nwar preparations which have been\nunder way in Britain since the first\nof the year.\nIt is not assured that such an au\nthorization will be asked by the ad\nministration. But even if it should\nbe. or if only a billion were sought,\nthe stimulus to business volume as a\nwhole, from all indications, would not\nbe great. Some lines, naturally, would\nbe materially benefitted.\nIt seems doubtful, if the govern\nment should engage in any such pro\ngram, that its 1938 expenditures could\nbe increased b> much more than $250,-\n000,000 aver this year.\nIn the current fiscal year, the ag\ngregate expenditures for national de\nfense\u2014that is, the total expenditures\nfor the army and navy\u2014may total\naround $1,200,000,000, including emer\ngency outlays. Of this amount. Stand\nard Statistics company in a monthly\nsurvey, calculates all but about $300,-\n000,000 represents the routine costs of\nmaintenance. Thus, what might be\nclassified as rearmament would come\nwithin $300,000,000. and this not only\nincludes new battleships, but also the\nwork of developing new plans, which\ncall for a high experimentation cost.\nWhile $300,000,000 is a substantial\nsum, it does not bulk large in the\nnation\u2019s gigantic Industrial totals.\nThere is another factor about a\nhuge war-preparing outlay which en\ngages the concern of business men.\nAny such additional expenditure as\na billion dollars or more would either\nthrow the budget further out of bal\nance. and might rouse new inflation\nary fears, or would necessitate new\ntaxation.\nLA FOLLETTE FEAT\nAMAZES WISCONSIN\nDemocrats and Republicans\nTalk of Huey Long as Gov\nernor Forces Bills Through\nLegislature\nMadison. Wis., Oct. 15\u2014(AP)\u2014Wis\nconsin Democrats and Republicans\nwho are talking of joining to oppose\nthe Progressive party stood frankly\namazed today at Gov Philip F. La\nFollette\u2019s achievement in pushing\nnearly a dozen controversial bills\nthrough the special session ot the\nLegislature In one week.\nThey likened hix control over the\nlawmaking body, which adjourns to-\nI morrow, to that of the late Huey\ni Long of Louisiana.\nAdded to the statute books, which\nalready contains laws pioneering in\nthe field of social and tax legislation,\nwas an act which indirectly puts the\nstate in the farm promotion busineM.\nAnother gives the executive office.\nI with the aid of a legislative commit*\nt*e. complete .control over reorganiz\ning the functions of state govern\nmental departments. Nine other bills\naffecting situations peculiar to the\nI state\u2014although highly controversial\nwere adopted.\nThe governor's rule over the Legis\nlature. which he claimed wag Justi\nfied by factional differences that\nstalled legislative proceedings, will be\nthe outstanding political Issue in the\nnext state campaign, opponents of the\nProgressives say.\nOn this score they believe this cam\npaign may see some form of coalition\nlof the old parties pooling their\nstrength to overthrow La Follette and\nI his Progressives,\nEstimated Deficit Raised to\n$695,245,000 by Roosevelt\nWashington, Oct. 18 (AP)\u2014\nI President Roosevelt hiked his esti\nmate of the federal deficit for this\nj fiscal year by $277,000,000 today,\nforecasting the treasury would run\n$895,246,000 into the red by next\nJune 30.\nRevamping the budget issued last\nj April, the President whittled his\nI estimate of revenues by $256,000,000\nbringing the figure down to $6,650,-\n410,000. He said spending would be\n$21,000,000 greater than anticipated\nand would total $7,345,655,000 ex\nclusive of $200,000,000 for debt re\ntirement.\nRevenue Drop Unexplained\nThe estimated gross deficit of $895.-\n215.000 included the $200,000,000 to be\napv A ...g Vj\u2019.'C\n|of this, the net deficit was forecast\nat $695,245,000. compared with a fore-\ncast of $418,000,000 last April and a\nI net deficit of $2,707,347,000 in the fiscal\nyear ended lune 30.\nMr Roosevelt gave no .reason for\nhis sharp reduction in the revenue\nestimate for this year, but authorities\nassumed it was predicated on the\nsevere stock market decline and recent\ndownswings in various business in\ndices.\nOn the spending side, the chief ex\necutive said numerous factors had\narisen since last April to increase\nspending, including expanded outlays\nfor the railroad retirement program,\nlegislation authorizing unemployment\ntax refunds under the social security\nact and extension of the Public Works\nadministration for two years.\nHe served notice that he was draw\ning the purse strings on outlays by\nboth the Public Works administra\ntion and the big Reconstruction Fi\nnance corporation, pioneer emergency\nlending agency which has pumped out\nbillions of dollars into channels of\nfinance, business and industry.\nNo More RFC Commitments\nIn the future. Mr Roosevelt said,\nthe RFC will make no further com\nmitments for loans. In addition, he\nsaid, commitments already on its\nbooks which may later be canceled\nwill not be used for expenditure on\nother comirfltments, but will be \"com\npletely cleared from the books, thus\ninsuring the elimination of such po\ntential charges against future\nbudgets.\u201d\nAlthough saying cancelation of any\ncommitments it is not called upon to\nmeet will not make the RFC return\nmoney to the treasury, the President\nsaid \u201cthe ultimate effect of such ac\ntion would relieve the treasury of a\nsubstantial potential liability, and to\nthis extent the budget outlook would\nbe improved.\u201d\nThe President previously had an\nnounced that no further commitments\nwould be made by the Public Works\nadministration. His statement today\nTROUBLE LOOMS\nFOR CONGRESS\u2019S\nSPECIAL SESSION\nBlack Affair, Antilynching\nBill, Democratic Division\nMay Eclipse Tasks Set by\nPresident\nWashington, Oft. 16 (AP)\nTroubles galore were predicted for\nthe new and special session of Con\ngress todaj \u2014not all of them origi\nnating in (he programs requested by\nPresident Roosevelt. The items for\nwhich he asked\u2014crop control, more\nnatural resource planning regions,\nwage and hour legislation, govern\nment reorganization and an anti\ntrust bill\u2014are all loaded with con\ntroversy, it is true, but there are\nother disputes lurking nearby.\nBlack Row Continues\nThe first of these is the continuing\nrow over the appointment of Hugo L.\nBlack to the supreme court, a dis\npute involving both his admitted for\nmer membership in the Ku Klux Klan\nand the question of his technical eligi\nbility under the constitution.\nPresident Roosevelt apparently has\ndetermined to say nothing more about\nthe case. But that does not go for\nsome members ot Congress. An im\npeachment effort before the session is\na tew days old would not surprise\nmany. Row No 2 is a congressional\nperennial. Not a session passes but\nthat the question of enacting anti\nlynching legislation does not bob up\nto produce an unyielding filibuster by\nsouthern senators. Before Congress\nadjourned In August, an agreement\nwas reached making an antilynching\nMil the Senate's second order of busi\nness, after the current recess.\nGauging the prospects for contro\nversy, Washington was prone to add\nto these, the disturbance within the\nDemocratic party left over from last\nsession\u2019s fight over the Roosevelt\nI court reform bill. Mr Roosevelt has\nsaid he may or may not recommend\nsuch legislation again. He did not\nmention it when he called the spe\ncial session.\nSo long ax the subject remains In\nthis status, the foes of last session\u2019s\nbill, including a good many Demo\ncrats. will obviously be constantly,\nand some ot them perhaps pugna\npiously nn the alert. The President's\nfive-point program itself holds abun\ndant promise of controversy. Crop\ncontrol Is a fighting phrase with some\nPrivate Relief Activities\nNeed Supporting\u2014Roosevelt\nHyde Park, X. Y.. Oct. 18\u2014(AP)\u2014\nPresident Roosevelt declared tonight\nthat local and private relief activities\n\"must be increased\" as federal help\nfor the needy is curtailed In an ef\nfort to balance the budget and avoid\nhigher taxes.\nIn a nationwide radio appeal from\nhis Hyde Park home for \"generous\u201d\nsupport by the people in the annual\nCommunity Chest relief fund drive, he\nsaid the nation must not become\n\"blinded by the welcome light of re\nturning prosperity to the very real\nneed that still exists for a consider\nable part of our population.\"\n\"The federal government with the\nreturn of prosperity.\" he added, \"must\nmore and more narrow the circle of\nIts relief activities and reduce the\namount of federal revenue to be ex\npended In the amelioration of human\nwant and distress In the various com\nmunities of our land.\n\"I say this because we all agree\nthat unless federal taxes are to be\ngreatly increased, the expenditures\nhave to be brought within the exist\ning tax receipts.\n\"Although federal government re\nlief activities have to be curtailed,\nthere must needs be no abatement\nsaid that the PWA probably will not\nbe called upon to meet all outstand\ning commitments, and that this will\ntend to brighten the budget picture.\nPWA Funds Back to Treasury\nMr Roosevelt asserted that balances\nnot required to take care of the PWA\nprogram already approved will be im\npounded and returned to the treasury,\nexclusive of $15,000,000 for administra\ntive expenses.\n\"The amount thus to be written off\nthe books will exceed $100,000,000i\u201d Mr\nRoosevelt said.\nIo a recent address, he said the\nbudget for the next fiscal year, start\ning July 1, 1938, would be \"definitely\nbalanced.\"\nHis aids in Congress frequently\nhave expressed hope that spending\nI could be brought within income with\nout additional taxes. The increased\ndeficit estimate for this fiscal year,\nhowever, Immediately aroused specu\nlation as to whether it would be pos\nsible to balance next year's accounts\nwithout raising tax levies.\nThe treasury now is studying the\nentire tax structure, and it was hinted\nrecently that consideration is being\ngiven to hiking rates on middle-bracket\nincomes.\nNo Mention of Next Year\nTreasury officials, however, declined\nto say whether the revised schedule\nof revenues and spending indicated\nheavier taxation would be necessary\nto put next year's budget into balance.\nIn his budget statement today, the\nPresident made no mention of the\nnext fiscal year.\nWhen he forecast the $418,000,000\nnet deficit last April, the President\nsaid he hoped this could be eliminated\nthrough government economies and\nthe liquidation of assets held by\nemergency lending agencies.\nHe said today that increases in\nsome expenditures resulting from\nlegislation or other factors would be\noffset in part by a $323,000,000 saving\nIn other outlays.\nThe order regarding commitments\nby the RFC and the PWA presumably\nrepresented an effort by the President\nto speed that part of his April pro\ngram calling for liquidation of assets.\nMr Roosevelt reduced the April\nestimate of federal receipts from\n$6,906,000,000 to $6,650,000,000. The.\nestimate of expenditures was left ap\nproximately unchanged, being in\ncreased only about $20,000,000 to\n$7,345,000,000.\nThe President said that general ex\npenditures this year would be about\n$156,000,000 above those during the\nlast fiscal period, due largely to higher\noutlays for highways, the Maritime\ncommission, national, defense and so\ncial security.\nSpending for \u201crecovery and relief,\u201d\nhowever, will total $1,139,000,000 less\nthan last fiscal year, the executive\nforecast.\nMr Roosevelt said this year's re\nceipts will top those of last year by\n$1,357,000,000. with income taxes pour\ning an additional $634,000,000 into the\nfederal till.\nsegments of the congressional mem\nbership. and there undoubtedly will be\nI much acrimonious discussion of the\ninterpretation that should be placed\nupon the supreme court decision\nwhich outlawed the old AAA.\nWage, Hour Legislation\nWage and hour legislation has\nvehement opposition among the\nsoutherners. It passed the Senate last\nsession only to be pigeonholed a\ncombination of Republicans and\nsouthern Democrats in the House\nrules committee. The first problem\nwhere it Is concerned is to get the\nbill out of committee.\nChairman O'Connor of the rules\ncommittee said this week that the\nbill would be sent to the House early\nin the session, presumably by a shift\nof votes within the coalition which\ntrapped the bill last year. If this\nshould fail to come about, a petition\nsigned by 218 members of the House,\na majority, would bring the measure\nto the floor.\nGovernment reorganization and the\nidea of tffiilding new power-resource\ndevelopments in major watersheds\nboth ran into abundant opposition at\nthe last session. A continuation of\nthe disputes then engendered was\nconsidered inevitable. Knowing noth\ning of what may be proposed in the\nway of new antitrust legislation, the\n(capital was uncertain Just how much\nof a fight would result. Ordinarily,\nI that subject is loaded with dynamite.\nLABOR SECRETARY\nVISITS PRESIDENT\nHyde Park. N. Y\u201e Oct. 17\u2014(API-\nLabor problems and wage-hour leg\nislation received President Roosevelt s.\nprimary attention today as Secretary\nPerkins detoured here on her way to\nWashington to make a personal re\nport.\nThe labor department secretary, on\nher w f ay to the capital from Connecti\ncut. came to the temporary White\nHouse of her own motion.\nShe found the chief executive en\ngaged in gathering data on which to\nbase his message to the special ses\nsion of Congress next month, on\nwhose calendar minimum wages, max\nimum hours and anti-child labor leg\nislation have been placed second to\nsurplus crop control.\nThe two also had an opportunity\nto go over the whole labor situation\nand the filling of the important post\nof assistant secretary of labor made\nvacant recently by the resignation\nof Edward F. McGrady.\nThe President interrupted consul\ntations with Samuel I. Rosenman.\nNew York state supreme court jns\ntlce. to talk with the only woman\ncabinet officer.\nat state, local and Individual relief\nwork. Indeed local and private activi\nties must be Increased.\"\nThe President spoke on program of\nthe community mobilization tor hu\nman needs. He was Introduced by\nCharles P. Taft, organization chair\nman, who spoke after the President\nfrom the Carnegie Music hall In\nPittsburg where Community Chest\nleaders gathered to map the money\ncampaign In 434 cities. He said the\nnation must not forget that there are\n\"people still hungry, their children un\ndernourished; that rags are the cloth\ning of many of our countrymen and\nmiserable shacks or crowded city\ntenements their only home.\"\nHe made a special appeal that \"fed\neral officials and our government em\nployes wherever they are found ought\nto take a leading part in cooperating\nwith local and community relief work\ners tn carrying forward their unremit\nting\" campaign. Citing the mutual aid\nexample of the city of Denver which\nhaa given to other cities, he said:\n\"Denver. 1 am informed. Is observ\ning tonight the ttfleth anniversary ot\nJoint financing. The Denver begin\nning was forerunner ot what has\nbeen developed Into the 450 Communi\nty Chests ot ths country.\u201d\nSTRAUS APPOINTED\nADMINISTRATOR OF\nHOUSINGPROGRAM\nFormer NRA Executive to\nBe in Charge of $526,-\n000,000 Setup\u2014Several\nOthers Sought Position\nHyde Park, N. Y\u201e Oct. 18\u2014 (AP)\u2014\nPresident Roosevelt set in motion the\nfederal government's vast new low\ncost housing and slum clearance pro\ngram by appointing Nathan Straus,\ndr New York citv, as administrator.\nThe youngish Straus, long a student\nof housing problems in the New York\nmetropolitan area, will take over his\nnew SIO,OOO post Wednesday after a\nconference at the White House with\nthe President and Secretary Ickes.\nHis title will be administrator of\nthe United States housing authority,\na division created in the\nSteagall act under Ickes\u2019s interior de\npartment. He will have control of a\n$526,000,000 long range program aimed\nat elimination of big city slums and\nprovision of low-rent homes and\napartments for the poorer classes.\nSeveral After Post\nThe appointment was announced\nafter Straus emerged from a long con\nference with the President, at the\ntemporary White House. Son of an\nold philanthropic family in New York,\nStraus won out over several other\ncandidates for the job. including How\nard Grav. chief of the public works\nadministration\u2019s housing section; John\nIhlder, alley-dwelling authority of the\nDistrict of Columbia, and I^mgdon\nW. Post, chairman of the housing\nauthority of New York city of\nwhich Straus Is a member.\nGray is understood to have been\nIckes's candidate, although officials\nwould not discuss rival sponsors.\nStraus, a small and slender man in\nhis 40's, has been in the government\nservice before. In the old NRA days\nhe was in charge of the blue, eagle\noffices in New York.\nHe was frequently consulted by the\nPresident when the new housing act\nwas under consideration In Congress\nlast session. A Democrat, he has on\noccasions dabbled in city politics.\nHousing has come more or less as a\nhobby to him. He has made housing\nstudies here and abroad for Mayor\nLa Guardia, an ardent advocate of\nthe federal program.\nWith more than half a billion dol\nlars at his disposal In the next four\nor five years, he will take over one\nof the most stupendous tasks created\nby the new deal in some time. For\nloans and grants to local housing\ngroups and initial capital he will have\nthe proceeds of a $500,000,000 bond\nissue and $26,000,000 in cash. Under\nthe act, capital grants or subsidies\nmay be made in lump sum or in an\nnual contributions spread over a long\nterm of years.\nLoans also will be made at low\nrates of interest and local capital will\npay part of the ultimate cost. Straus\nwas the only business caller at the\nRoosevelt home during the day. The\nPresident again worked on official\nmail, compiled a radio address\nopening the annual drive for the com\nmunity mobilization for human needs,\nand prepared to leave for Washington\ntomorrow night.\nHe will dedicate the new Federal\nReserve board building there Wednes\nday afternoon and probably return\nhere next weekend to remain until\nafter election day.\nKANSAS CITY FORD\nSHUTDOWN MAY BE\nMADEPERMANENT\nCompany Charges Police\nRefused Officials Access to\nPlant Except On Union\nPass During Strike\nDetroit, Oct. 14\u2014(AP)\u2014The Ford\nMotor company, charging that an \u201cin\ntolerable\" situation had arisen because\nof the picketing of its Kansas City\nplant, indicated today that it was con\nsidering closing the plant permanently.\n\u201cI do not think there is anything\nto do but close the plant,\" said Harry\nH. Bennett, personnel director, \"but\nthat Is up to the company. We can\u2019t\nget police protection. The Ford Motor\ncompany doesn\u2019t, work that way. As\nfar as I\u2019m concerned \u2014if I have any\nthing to say about it \u2014we\u2019r^ all\nthrough in Kansas City.\"\nH. C. Doss, manager of the Kansas\nCity plant which has been picketed\nsince Monday by the United Automo\nbile Workers' of America, and J. S.\nBush, plant superintendent, were In\nDearborn to confer with Ford of\nficials.\nA company statement said Doss had\nbeen refused entrance to his office at\nKansas City except on a union pass.\n\u201cKansas City police refused protec\ntion to any Ford official who did not\nhold a union pass,\" the statement\nsaid. \"Regarding this condition as in\ntolerable, the Ford Motor company\nwithdrew Its manager and plant su\nperintendent.\u201d\nThe statement was issued after City\nManager H. F. McElroy, of Kansas\nCity, had telephoned assurance to\nDoss that any Ford executive or of\nfice worker could have access to the\ncompany's plant there.\nOnly 150 maintenance men have\nbeen at work in the Kansas City\nplant since September 15 because of\nthe changeover to 1938 model produc\ntion. They were laid off Monday when\npicketing ot the plant began and the\nother 3000 employes were advised to\nfind work elsewhere because reopen\ning plans were Indefinite,\nU, A. W. A. leaders described the\ncircumstance as a lockout. Bennett\nsaid It wax a dispute between \"the\nC. I. O. and some other union.\"\nDuring a sit-down strike last\nspring. Bennett told union leaders the\nplant would be moved if the strike\ncontinued.\nToday. Bennett said it was un\ncertain to what, plant operations of\nthe Kansas City plant would be\ntransferred If it were closed\npermanently. He Indicated the Dallas\n(Tex.) plant might, receive some of\nthe work.\n\"Company Union\" Charged\nKansas City, Mo.. Oct. 14\u2014\" Co\nmpany union\" was the label placed to\nday upon the Independent union of\nFnrd workers of greater Kansas City\nby Baron de Louis. president ot the\nlocal unit of the United Automobile\nWorkers now on strike at the Ford\nassembly plant here.\nDe Louis charged that the Independ\nent union not only was inspired by\nthe Ford company, but that, workers\nwere coerced Into joining It He de\nclared affidavits were being taken\nfrom a I. O. members in which they\nwould swear to thia.\nDe Ix>uls denied he had any\nknowledge of the whereabouts of two\nFord employes reported kidnaped. He\nssti the men came voluntarily to\nC. I. O. headquarters to Join the union\nand were signed up. He asked:\n\"Why should we want to harm\nthem?'\nJung Calls Religion\nDominant Influence\nIn Human Behavior\nNew York, Oct. 15\u2014(AP)\u2014Re\nligion, and not sex, was suggested\nas the dominant Influence in\nhuman behavior today by Dr Carl\nJung. 63-y ear-old professor of\npsychology at the Technical uni\nversity of Zurich, Switz.\nArriving here on the liner\nHansa to give the Terry lectures\nat Yale university, -Dr Jung dis\nputed the much-debated theories\nof Dr Sigmund Freud.\nHuman reactions are based\n\u201cmuch more on religious phe\nnomena than on sex,\" he asserted.\n\"Everything seems to be based\nupon a person's religious outlook.\"\nHe defined religion, however, as\nnot simply a spiritual matter but\nan outlook that might lead, for\nexample, to bolshevism or a perse\ncution complex.\nTHREAT OF DEATH\nMADE TO DOCTOR\nIN SYPHILIS WAR\nChicago\u2019s Board of Health\nHead Puts Quarantine Sign\nOn Brothel, Receives\nWarning in Mail\nChicago, Oct. 18\u2014(AP)\u2014A move to\nextend the city's antisyphilis cam\npaign to vice resorts brought threats\nof death today to Dr Herman N.\nBundesen, president, of the board of\nhealth. He disclosed he had received\na letter this, morning which\nwarned:\n\"You are going to get som lead\npills and- pineapples to digest.\n\"You won't nail any more signs up\non doors in a hurry you snak faced\nlouse.\"\nIt was signed by \"Bllacksman. vul\ntures of Chicago,\" and \"Poison Pete.\u201d\nProcurer is Blamed\nThe poorly spelled\u2014in some places\nobscene\u2014message was written on\ncheap paper and was dropped in the\nmails last night. A skull and cross\nbones was sketched on the bottom.\nDr Bundesen attributed the note to\na vice procurer who feared his liveli\nhood was threatened. He turned it\nover to federal investigators. He also\nsaid he had received similar threats\nover the telephone Saturday night.\nLast Friday. Dr Bundesen tacked a\nvenereal disease quarantine placard\non the door of a west side brothel.\nThe anonymous caller warned the\nfollowing night, he said, that he\nwould \u201cget a pineapple\" it he didn\u2019t\nremove it.\nLater he learned the sign had been\ntorn down and went out to the place\nand put up a new one.\n\u201cWe won't be bullied or bluffed,\u201d\nDr Bundesen declared. \"This drive is\nstarted and it\u2019s going to be finished.\"\nBundesen is one of the directors of\nthe city-wide drive to stamp out\nsyphilis. The campaign\u2014first ever at\ntempted in the United States on such\na broad scale \u2014has attracted wide in\nterest.\nARKANSAS ELECTS\nMILLER TO SENATE\nSEAT OF ROBINSON\nGov Bailey Concedes Defeat\nWhen Count Reaches 59,-\n465 to 38,870 Against\nHim \u2014Contest Bitter\nLittle Rocks. Ark.. Oct. 18\u2014 (AP)\u2014\nCongressman John E. Miller, Demo\ncrat running as an independent, won\nelection to the unexpired term of the\nlate Senate majority leader, Joseph\nT. Robinson, in today special general\nelection, defeating Gov Carl E. Bailey,\nstate Democratic committee nominee\nand ardent new dealer, by a handy\nmajority.\nBailey conceded the election at 9.35\np. m. on the basis of returns tabu\nlated by the Associated Press at that,\nhour. Bailey issued this statement:\n\u201cTo the People of Arkansas:\n\u201cI concede the election of Congress\nman Miller to succeed Senator Rob\ninson. I shall continue to serve you\nas governor to the best of my ability.\n\u201cCARL E. BAILEY\".\nThe Associated Press returns at the\nhour of the governor\u2019s statement\nshowed:\n1440 precincts out of 1923. for Mil\nler 59,465, for Bailey, 38.870. The\nelection was marked by the national\nadministration issue and by bitter\nfactional warfare within the predomi\nnant Democratic party. There was\nno P >ublican entry.\nMiller swept to victory in this tra\nditionally \"regular Democratic'\u2019 state\nin the face of Bailey's campaign cry\nthat a Miller victory would be \u201ca\nslap in the face for Franklin Delano\nRoosevelt.\u201d The governor repeatedly\ncharged Miller was \u201can nnti-Roose\nveit\" with Liberty league backing.\nBORAH HITS PLAN\nFOR G. ORSESSION\nOpposes Preconvention\nMeeting Because \u2018lt Would\nHave No Authority\u2019 to\nSpeak for Party\nBoise. Ida.. Oct. 18\u2014(AP)\u2014William\nE. Borah, Republican dean of the\nSenate, In a formal statement today\nsaid he \u201cstrongly advises against\" a\npreconvention meeting of the Repub\nlican party.\n\u201cThe great objection to the conven\ntion or gathering Is that It would\nhave no authority, no authenticity\nbehind It.\" he declared.\n\"A declaration of principles coming\nfrom (i body of self-selected delegates\nwould be nothing more than the\nviews ot those individuals.\n\u201cSuch a declaration might be fa\nfrom what the declaration would ba\nupon the party ot a delegation\nselected by the voters.\n\"If the leaders wish to give the\npublic their views, those views would\ndoubtless be interesting but such\nviews could not In any sense lie ac\ncepted mi the views of the party.\n\"Furthermore, if such views are\nput out as Being party views, I be\nlieve a wide controversy will start at\nonce. In fact, there would be no bet\nter way to stir discord than to start\nsuch a convention. We should wait\nuntil tha voters can choose their dele\ngates.\n\u201cUTTIZHoANGBR^OF war\nSt Louis, Oct. 17-(AP)-There Is\n'little danger\" of another world war,\nHennen Swaffer, chief editorial writer\not the London Daily Hersld, declared\nin an interview here today.\nSTRINGENT RULES\nFOR AIR TRAFFIC\nGIVENOUT BY U. S.\nRigid Regulations for Instru\nment Flying With Poor\nVisibility Take Effect No\nvember I\nWashington, Oct. 17\u2014(AP) \u2014New\nand stringent air traffic rules to mako\nflying safer will go into effect Novem\nber 1.\nThe regulations, announced today,\nare the result of nearly two years\nstudy by the bureau of air commerce\nin airway traffic control.\nTwo types of flight rules are estab\nlished. The first are fqr contact\nflights (those made when weather con\nditions are sufficiently good to pre\nclude collision hazards), the second\nfor Instrument Rights (made when,\nweather conditions are such 't' J\nplanes might not avoid collision h S\na rds unless definite restrictions\nimposed;.\nUnder the new air traffic rules Mu\u2019\ntact flights may be made under vir\ntually no restrictions other thanbroa\n\"rules of the road.\u201d\nInstrument flights, however, must\nbe made under rigid restrictions. For\nexample:\u2014\nPilots must have an instrument rat\ning and their planes must carry com\nplete Instrument equipment, including\ntwo-way radio.\nA definite flight plan\u2014including in\nformation on the point of first ir j\ntended landing, proposed cruising if\ntitudes and airspeeds. estimai J\nelapsed time until arrival at destir 1,\ntion. and an alternate airport\u2014mi a\nbe submitted and approved before\nparture. j\nGreen. Amber and Red\nPilots shall not make changes in\ntheir flight plans while in the sir\nwithout the approval of the station\narea in which the flight is progress\ning.\nGreen, amber and red airways arg\nmarked out with prescribed altltU'A\nlevels and altitude crossing leve\nGreen airways have the right of w.\namber gives way to the green, h W\nthe red to both amber and green.\u2019\nA weather minimum of 506-fr X\nceiling and one-mile visibility is pr\u00ab-1\nscribed, below which none but sebed-,\nuled or military aircraft may operate\nControled airports and zones ar.,\ndefined. A controled airport is one\nwhere directional radio facilities are\nestablished, and a controled zone as\nthe area within a three-mile radius\nof a controled airport.\nPlanes must carry sufficient f(ie!\nnot only to complete the projected\nflight, but also enough to reach an\nalternate airport and still have\nenough' for 45 minutes additional\nflight.\nWOULD SACRIFICE\n\u2018SOME EFFICIENCY\u2019\nTO AVOID TYRANN V\nGlenn Frank Says Founded\n\u2018Wisely\u2019 Set Safeguard\nAgainst CentralizatioW\nPreferring Some Waste 1\nWashington. Oct. 15\u2014Centralization\nof governmental power always ends\nin tyranny and founders of the re\npublic were \u201cwise\" in sacrificing \"some\nefficiency\" in government as a safe\nguard against despotism. Glenn Fran) J\nformer University of Wisconsin pres a\ndent, declared tonight before th\u00ae\nWashington board of trade.\nIn an address which some associa\u00df\ntion members interpreted as an attae\non new deal policies, Frank declared I\n\"Centralization of power, even wherl\ndesigned to serve emergency ends\nonly, has always moved relentlessly\nin the direction of self-perpetuation.\nAnd it has scorned no weapon that\nwould advance It on the road of per\nmanent power. It has always sought\nto bully into silence minority opinion\nwithin and without its own ranks,\".\nThe theory that \u201cstrong govern J\nment\u201d is a pressing need of the da\nis a \u201cmajor delusion,\" Frank tol\nboard members who were hosts t\nprominent civic and political leade\nincluding John D. M. Hamilton, chai\nman of the Republican national coni\nmittee: Senator Millard Tydings, JE\not Maryland; Representative St\nBloom. (D) of New York and Assis\nant Secretary of War Col Louis Johit\nson.\nLEHMAN INDORSES\nJUDGE MAHONEY\nMAYORALTY RAC\nGovernor Enters New Yor\nCity\u2019s Political Campaig\nBacking LaGuardia\u2019s Ne\u00bb\nDeal Opponent\nNew York, Oct. 16 (AP) \u2014Grj\nHerbert H. Lehman entered 'Nef\nYork city's political campaign today\nwith the election 17 days off\u2014by pr<\nclaiming his support of former Judf\nJeremiah T. Mahoney, Democrat\u2019\ncandidate for mayor.\nLehman, himself a Democrat, so\nlowed the lead of Postmaster-Genera\nJames A. Farley and United Shite\nSenators Robert F. Wagner ar\nRoyal S. Copeland by indorsing tt\nTammany backed new deal opponen\nof Mayor Florello H. LaGuardia,\nis also an avowed new deal enthu\nsiast. LaGuardia la being supports\nfor reelection by the fusion. Reput\nllcan, American Labor and oth<\nminority parties. 1\nIn a letter to Mahoney, Lehman\ndescribed the candidate as \"a man\nwho, by character, ability and traiyf\ning, is equipped in every way to t I\nminister the affairs of the city c.\nNew York.\"\nThe governor said \"I shall be Very\nglad Indeed to vote for you and for\nyour associates. Frank J. Taylor and\nMax J. Schneider.\" the Democratic\ncandidates for controller and president\nof the. council.\nSenator Wagner, life-long friend of\nMahoney, will make his first speech\nin behalf of the Democratic ticket at.\na labor rally Monday night, sponsored\ni by nn American Federation of Labor\naffiliate's committee.\nAnnouncement of the meeting came\ntoday as George A. Meany, president\nof the state Federation of Labor, Is\nsued a statement, denouncing the re\ncently organized Trades Union Party\nfor Mahoney, which has petltldned\nfor a. place on election ballots.\n\"It is as fictitious and fraudulent,\nfrom stem to stern, as a three dollar\nbill,\" said Meany, adding \"the A. F. L.\nis practically unanimous in support\nof LaGuardia In this campaign.\"","height":"25970","width":"20063"}}
